\newthought{Senate question}. The simulation (\ref{subsec:senate_micro}) shows a near normal distribution with mean=23 and standard deviation=1.75. The micro-macro effect (\ref{subsec:senata_micro_macro}) would keep them at 49 seats. 
The chances that
\begin{itemize}
  \item for the Democrats to have a majority of 53 and more means they need to win at least 4 extra seats. In the micro simulation (mean=23) that would mean 27 or more. The probability for that is \Sexpr{100*sum(race.senate.result>26)/N}\%
  \item the probability that the Democrats have a majority less than 53 (51 or 52 senators) is \Sexpr{100*sum(race.senate.result==25)/N + 100*sum(race.senate.result==26)/N}\%
  \item the probability that Republicans have a majority less than 53 (50, 51 or 52 senators) is \Sexpr{100*sum(race.senate.result==22)/N + 100*sum(race.senate.result==23)/N + 100*sum(race.senate.result==24)/N}\%
  \item the probability that the Republicans have a majority of 53 and more is \Sexpr{100*sum(race.senate.result<22)/N}\%
\end{itemize}

This also means that the probability that the Democrats win the Senate is \Sexpr{100*sum(race.senate.result>24)/N}\%.

