    \item Democratic Party, with less than 230 representatives. Probability=\Sexpr{p2}\%
    \item Republican Party, with 230 or more representatives. Probability=\Sexpr{p4}\%
    \item Republican Party, with less than 230 representatives. Probability=\Sexpr{p3}\%
\end{itemize}

This also means that the probability that the Democrats win the House is \Sexpr{p1+p2}\%. 

\newthought{This calculation} shows that the result for the House elections is very volatile with regard to the degree of interconnectedness: an upgrade of 3\% shifts the mean number of seats for the Democrats from 215 to 227 (+5.6\%), almost the double of the upgrade! The standard deviation is the same for the result of the micro simulation and the result of the combined simulation ($\sigma=5.61$). Because of this volatility I reduce the effect of the upgrade to a maximum rise of the mean number of seats to the level of the upgrade itself. In this case: an upgrade of 3\% can only lead to 221=215*1.03 seats. The standard deviation is kept at 5.61. This gives the following estimates:

