\newthought{Again this calculation} shows that the result for the House elections is very volatile with regard to the degree of interconnectedness: an upgrade of 3\% shifts the mean number of seats for the Democrats from \Sexpr{round(mean(race.result.House.micro),0)} (a gain of \Sexpr{round(mean(race.result.House.micro),0)-193}) to \Sexpr{round(mean(race.result.House.combi),0)} (a gain of \Sexpr{round(mean(race.result.House.combi),0)-193} or +\Sexpr{round(100*(mean(race.result.House.combi)- mean(race.result.House.micro))/mean(race.result.House.micro),2)}\%)! 

In \ref{subsec:macrohouse} we constructed a linear model linking the president's approval rate (Gallup) with the number of House-seats gained or lost. For first time presidents the relation is given by:

\begin{equation}
  y = -140.5292 + 2.2224*x
\end{equation}

At the moment the approval rate of the president is 42\% which predicts that the Republicans could lose \Sexpr{round(-140.5292 + 2.2224*42,0)} seats. The 95\% confidence interval is [\Sexpr{round(-140.5292 + 2.2224*42 +15,0)},\Sexpr{round(-140.5292 + 2.2224*42 -15,0)}]. Our upgrade model for the House (+3\%) does not seem excessive because it predicts a loss for the Republicans of -\Sexpr{round(mean(race.result.House.combi),0)-193} which is at the low edge of the confidence interval.

The degree of volatility is still high so I still limit the upgrade effect to a maximum rise of the mean number of seats to the level of the upgrade itself. In this case: an upgrade of 3\% can only lead to \Sexpr{round(mean(race.result.House.micro)*1.03,0)} seats. The standard deviation is kept at \Sexpr{round(sd(race.result.House.combi),3)}. With these assumptions I get the following probabilities:

