The  simulation (with the revised ratings on the basis of the polling results) and with a moderate +3\% upgrade shows that the Democrats get on average \Sexpr{round(mean(race.result.Senate.combi),0)} seats. The probability of the Democrats winning the senate is still negligible: \Sexpr{round((p1+p2),0)}\%.

The probabilities for the Good Judgement question are:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Democratic Party, with 53 or more senators. Probability=\Sexpr{p1}\%
    \item Democratic Party, with less than 53 senators. Probability=\Sexpr{p2}\%
    \item Republican Party, with 53 or more senators. Probability=\Sexpr{p4}\%
    \item Republican Party, with less than 53 senators. Probability=\Sexpr{p3}\%
\end{itemize}

The reasons that make it so difficult for the Democrats to win the Senate are unchanged: they have to defend 26 seats while the Republicans just a third (9) of that number. Even if all the 26 Democratic seats were safe (which they are not), they would still need to take 2 seats from the 9 Republican incumbents. The Democrat's biggest opportunities are in Arizona and Nevada. In Arizona we will have to wait until the Republican primary on August 28th to see who will be running on the Republican side. In Nevada, the most recent polls still show that Heller and Rosen have the same support. There are at the moment no signs that these states move significantly towards the Democrats.

