The digitisation is more or less OK.

The remarkable thing is that the plot is not symmetrical: it has a long tail on the left side (fewer Republican seats). What is going on?
\begin{itemize}
  \item For the Democrats the number of ''Safe/Solid" seats is 191. According to 538 the minimum seats they gain is 187. In the worst case the Democrats keep about the number of ''Safe" seats
  \item For the Repbulicans the number of ''Safe/Solid" seats is 137. According to 538 the minimum seats they gain is 146. In the worst case the Republicans have a little more than their ''Safe" seats
  \item That means that the competition is for the 98 remaining seats which are dubbed ''Likely", ''Lean", ''Tilt" or ''Toss-up".
  \item There are 69 Republican seats ''Likely/Lean/Tilt" and only 23 Democratic seats. As we can see from the boxplots in Figur~\ref{fig:HouseCpopvote} there is no big difference in the estimate of the populare vote between Democrats and Republicans in the categories ''Likely" and ''Lean".
\end{itemize}

